==English==

===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|ML.|respectivus}}, from {{der|en|la|respectus}}. Equivalent to {{suffix|en|respect|ive}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ɹɪˈspɛktɪv/}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-respective.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɛktɪv}}
* {{hyph|en|re|spec|tive}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|-}}

# Relating to particular persons or things, each to each; particular; own.
#: ''They returned to their '''respective''' places of abode.''
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=August 23, 2012|author=Alasdair Lamont|title=Hearts 0-1 Liverpool| work=BBC Sport| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19279553| passage=Adam and Novikovas swapped long-range efforts, neither of which troubled the '''respective''' keepers.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2020 April 22|title=Network News: Staged return to work at Hitachi and CAF factories|journal=Rail|page=9|text=Hitachi and CAF have begun a staged return to work at their '''respective''' [[Newton Aycliffe]] and [[Newport]] factories, having reduced output following the [[COVID-19]] outbreak.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Noticing with attention; [[careful]]; [[wary]].
#* {{rfdatek|en|Archbishop Sandys}}
#*: If you look upon the church of England with a '''respective''' eye, you can not {{...}} refuse this charge.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Looking toward; having reference to; relative, not absolute.
#: ''the '''respective''' connections of society''
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Fitted to awaken [[respect]].
#* '''1599''', [[w: William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]], ''[[s: The Two Gentlemen of Verona (Shakespeare; First Folio)|The Two Gentlemen of Verona]]'', IV. iv. 192:
#*: What should it be that he respects in her / But I can make '''respective''' in myself,
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Rendering respect; [[respectful]]; [[regardful]].
#* {{rfdatek|en|Chapman}}
#*: With '''respective''' shame, rose, took us by the hands.
#* {{rfdatek|en|Lord Burleigh}}
#*: With thy equals familiar, yet '''respective'''.

